The MoS was estimated based on an initial sleep/wake scoring ML model and thereafter aligning a cosine function with a wavelength of 24 h such that the maximum value of 1 corresponds to the MoS.22 The equation for the estimated circadian rhythm cosine function is \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$circ\left(t \right) = \cos \left({{{2\pi } \over {24}} \cdot \left({{t_h} - {\mu _h} + {{{t_m} - {\mu _m}} \over {60}}} \right)} \right)$\end{document}, with the current time stamp t, hour of the current time stamp th, minute of the current time stamp tm, estimated MoS μ, hour of the estimated MoS μh, and minute of the estimated MoS μm. Figure 1J shows the estimated MoS and circadian rhythm curve for one participant. To estimate the MoS, we used the sleep/wake predictions of the initial ML model not trained on the estimated circadian rhythm data to determine the sleep-onset and sleep-offset for each participant (see details in section 2.4). A slightly modified version of the definition suggested by Fekedulegn and collegues24 was used to compute sleep-onset and sleep-offset, ie, sleep-onset was defined as the time point of the first continuous period of at least 20 min of sleep with no more than 1 min of sleep interruption, while sleep-offset was defined as the last minute scored as sleep before a period of at least 2 h of wakefulness. MoS was defined as the midpoint in time between sleep-onset and sleep-offset, ie, computed as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$\mu = {1 \over 2}\left({{\sigma _{on}} + {\sigma _{off}}} \right)$\end{document}, with μ being the MoS, σon the sleep-onset, and σoff the sleep-offset.25

We used a grid search with four-fold cross-validation for hyperparameter optimization to find good hyperparameters for each input strategy. The macro F1-score is used as the primary metric to determine the best hyperparameters, defined as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage[substack]{amsmath}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage[mathscr]{eucal}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\DeclareFontFamily{T1}{linotext}{}
\DeclareFontShape{T1}{linotext}{m}{n} {linotext }{}
\DeclareSymbolFont{linotext}{T1}{linotext}{m}{n}
\DeclareSymbolFontAlphabet{\mathLINOTEXT}{linotext}
\begin{document}
$F1 = 2 \cdot {{precision \cdot sensitivity} \over {precision + sensitivity}}$\end{document}. In contrast to accuracy, the F1-score is more robust against class imbalances in the dataset (ie, the much greater number of sleep epochs as compared to wake). After the hyperparameter optimization, a leave-one-subject-out (LOSO) cross-validation was performed for each input strategy, using the best hyperparameters of the grid searches. In an LOSO cross-validation, the classifier is trained on the data from all participants except one (N-1) which is kept out and used as the test data. This is repeated N times so that each participant is used as a test participant once. The average specificity (true negative rate), average sensitivity (true positive rate), and average F1-score across the N different runs of each LOSO cross-validation are reported to indicate the overall performance of the ML model.
